Here is the function you can use in Julia programming language:

```julia
function clean_column(col) 
    return replace(lowercase(strip(col)), ' ' => "_") |> replace('-' => "_")
end
```
This function first converts `col` to lowercase and strips any leading or trailing whitespaces using the `strip()` function. Then, it replaces all spaces with underscores using `replace()`. The `|>` operator is used here for readability but you can also use parentheses `( )` to achieve the same result.

However, if your column name has a hyphen and not a space then you might want to replace only one instance of the hyphen or use a different character as separator:

```julia
function clean_column(col) 
    return replace(lowercase(strip(col)), ' -' => "_") |> replace('-' => "_")
end
```
